Definition 7. A partition $\lambda$ is a finite or infinite sequence of integers $(\lambda_{1},\lambda_{2},$ $\dots,\lambda_{i},\dots)$, with $\lambda_{1}\geq\lambda_{2}\geq\dots\geq 0$ and $\mid\lambda\mid:=\sum_{i}\lambda_{i}<\infty,$ so that, from a certain point onwards (if $\lambda$ is infinite), all the $\lambda_{i}$ are $0$. The non zero $\lambda_{i}$ are called the parts of $\lambda$. The number of parts is the length $l(\lambda)$ of $\lambda$.
Definition 3. Given $m$, $n$, $k$, three nonnegative integers such that $\;m,\;n\geq 1$, then the polynomial ring $\displaystyle\mathbb{Z}({\bf a}_{1},{\bf a}_{2},\dots,{\bf a}_{m},{\bf a}_{1% \mu},{\bf a}_{2\mu},\dots,{\bf a}_{m\mu},{\bf a}_{1\mu_{1}\mu_{2}},{\bf a}_{2% \mu_{1}\mu_{2}},\dots,{\bf a}_{m\mu_{1}\mu_{2}},\dots,$ $\displaystyle\;\;\;\,{\bf a}_{1\mu_{1}\mu_{2}\dots\mu_{k}},{\bf a}_{2\mu_{1}% \mu_{2}\dots\mu_{k}},\dots,{\bf a}_{m\mu_{1}\mu_{2}\dots\mu_{k}}),$ where $\mu,\;\mu_{1},\;\mu_{2},\;\;\dots,\;\mu_{k-1}$ and $\;\mu_{k}$ take all values in $\left\{\,1,2,\dots,n\,\right\}$, is denoted by $\mathbb{Z}\left[{\bf a}_{m}{\bf a}_{m{\left[\mu\right]}_{k}}\right]$. The number of indeterminates is $mq_{k}$, where $q_{k}=\frac{n^{k+1}-1}{n-1}\;\;{\mbox{if}}\;\;n\neq 1;\;\;q_{k}=k+1,\;{\mbox{% if}}\;\;n=1.$ The symmetric group $S_{mq_{k}}$ defines the graded ring of symmetric polynomials of $\mathbb{Z}[{\bf a}_{m}{\bf a}_{m\left[\mu\right]_{k}}]$: $\Lambda_{m,k}=\mathbb{Z}[{\bf a}_{m}{\bf a}_{m{\left[\mu\right]}_{k}}]^{S_{mq_% {k}}}.$
Definition 2. Let $r$ be a nonnegative integer. The projective (or inverse) limit $\;\;\Lambda^{r}=\lim_{\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\longleftarrow}}{{n}}}\Lambda_{n}% ^{r}$ is the additive group of sequences of homogeneous symmetric polynomials of degree $r$ such that $f^{r}=(f_{1}^{r},f_{2}^{r},\dots,f_{n}^{r},\dots)$ with $\displaystyle\forall n\in\mathbb{N}\not\,\;\left\{0\right\},\;\;f_{n}^{r}\in% \Lambda_{n}^{r}\;\;\mbox{and}\;\;\pi_{n+1}(f_{n+1}^{r})=f_{n}^{r}.$ The elements of $\Lambda^{r}$ are called projective limits and $\Lambda^{r}$ is called the homogeneous group of degree $r$ of projective limits. Besides, let $\;\Lambda=\bigoplus_{r\geq 0}\Lambda^{r}$ be the graded ring defined by the direct sum of the homogeneous groups $\Lambda^{r}$. An element $f$ of $\Lambda$ is a sum of projective limits, namely $f=\sum_{r\geq 0}f^{r}$ such that, for any degree $r$, $f^{r}$ belongs to the homogeneous group $\Lambda^{r}$. An element of $\Lambda$ is called a symmetric function.
Definition 5. Given $r$ a nonnegative integer, then (i) We call horizontal (resp. vertical) sequence (m,k) of degree $r$ the inverse system denoted by $(\Lambda_{m,k}^{r},h^{r}_{m,k})_{m\in\mathbb{N}}$, (resp. $(\Lambda_{m,k}^{r},v^{r}_{m,k})_{k\in\mathbb{N}}$); (ii) We call sequence (m,k) of degree $r$ the inverse system denoted by $(\Lambda_{m,k}^{r},\pi^{r}_{m,k})_{m,k\in\mathbb{N}}.$
Definition 1. Let ${\bf x}_{1},{\bf x}_{2},\ldots,{\bf x}_{n}$ be $n$ independent indeterminates, $S_{n}$ be the symmetric group of permutations of a set with $n$ elements acting on the polynomial ring ${\mathbb{Z}}\left[{\bf x}_{1},{\bf x}_{2},\ldots,{\bf x}_{n}\right]$ by permuting the indeterminates, i.e: $\displaystyle\forall P=a_{I}{\bf x}^{I}\in{\mathbb{Z}}\left[{\bf x}_{1},{\bf x% }_{2},\ldots,{\bf x}_{n}\right],$ $\displaystyle\forall\sigma\in S_{n},\;\;\;\sigma P=\sigma a_{I}{\bf x}^{I}=a_{% I}{\bf x}^{I}_{\sigma(\cdot)},$ where ${\bf x}={\bf x}_{1}{\bf x}_{2}\dots\bf x_{n}$, $a_{I}\in\mathbb{Z}$. $I=(i_{1},i_{2},\ldots,i_{k})$, with $0\leq i_{k}$ and $\;1\leq k\leq n$, denotes the usual multi-index notation (the implicit summation is used). Then, ${\Lambda}_{n}:={\mathbb{Z}}\left[{\bf x}_{1},{\bf x}_{2},\ldots,{\bf x}_{n}% \right]^{S_{n}}$ is the subring of ${\mathbb{Z}}\left[{\bf x}_{1},{\bf x}_{2},\ldots,{\bf x}_{n}\right]$ of symmetric polynomials obtained by permuting the ${\bf x}_{i}$.
Definition 6. Let $r$ be a nonnegative integer. Two symmetric functions $P^{r}$ and $Q^{r}$ of degree $r$ are said equal if and only if $\;\forall n\in\mathbb{N},\;\;P^{r}_{n}=Q^{r}_{n}$.
Definition 8. Given two nonnegative integers $m$ and $k$, we call a $\left[m,k\right]$-partition (or a multi-partition when no confusion occurs) the ordered sequence $\displaystyle\lambda_{\left[m,k\right]}=(\lambda^{\left[m,0\right]},\lambda^{% \left[m,1\right]},\dots,\lambda^{\left[m,k\right]})$ defined by a set of $k+1$ partitions such that: $\displaystyle\lambda^{\left[m,0\right]}=\lambda^{\left[m,0\right]}_{1\leq i}=(% \lambda^{\left[m,0\right]}_{1},\lambda^{\left[m,0\right]}_{2},\dots,\lambda^{% \left[m,0\right]}_{p},\dots),\;\;\lambda^{\left[m,1\right]}=(\lambda^{\left[m,% 1\right]}_{p\mu})_{1\leq p,\mu},$ $\displaystyle\lambda^{\left[m,k\right]}=({\lambda^{\left[m,k\right]}}_{p\mu_{1% }\mu_{2}\dots\mu_{k}})_{1\leq p,\mu_{1},\mu_{2},\dots,\mu_{k}},$ with $1\leq\mu_{l}\leq n,\;\;for\;\;1\leq l\leq k$, so that the following property is satisfied: $\displaystyle\lambda^{\left[m,0\right]}_{1}\geq\lambda^{\left[m,0\right]}_{2}% \geq\dots\geq\lambda^{\left[m,0\right]}_{p}\geq\dots\geq\lambda^{\left[m,0% \right]}_{m}\geq\dots\geq\lambda^{\left[m,1\right]}_{11}\geq$ $\displaystyle\lambda^{\left[m,1\right]}_{12}\geq\dots\geq\lambda^{\left[m,1% \right]}_{1\mu}\geq\dots\geq\lambda^{\left[m,1\right]}_{21}\geq\dots\geq% \lambda^{\left[m,1\right]}_{2\mu}\geq\dots\geq\lambda^{\left[m,1\right]}_{2n}\geq\dots$ $\displaystyle\geq\lambda^{\left[m,1\right]}_{p\mu}\geq\dots\lambda^{\left[m,1% \right]}_{m1}\geq\lambda^{\left[m,1\right]}_{m2}\geq\dots\geq\lambda^{\left[m,% 1\right]}_{mn}\geq\dots\geq\lambda^{\left[m,k\right]}_{m\mu_{1}\dots\mu_{k}}$ $\displaystyle\geq\lambda^{\left[m,k\right]}_{m\mu_{1}\dots(\mu_{k}+1)}\geq% \dots\geq 0.$ $\lambda^{\left[m,p\right]}$, for any $0\leq p\leq k$, is called a sub-partition of $\lambda_{\left[m,k\right]}$. Furthermore, we identify $\displaystyle\mid\lambda_{\left[m,k\right]}\mid=\sum_{0\leq p\leq k}\mid% \lambda^{\left[m,p\right]}\mid.$ The length of the $\left[m,k\right]$-partition is defined by the sum of the lengths of its sub-partitions, namely $\displaystyle l(\lambda_{\left[m,k\right]})=\sum_{0\leq p\leq k}l(\lambda^{% \left[m,p\right]}).$
Definition 4. Let $m$ and $k$ be nonnegative integers, $m\geq 1$. (i) The graded ring homomorphism $\;\;h_{m+1,k}:\Lambda_{m+1,k}\to\Lambda_{m,k},\;$ such that $\forall r\in\mathbb{N},\;\,$ $h_{m+1,k}\mid_{\Lambda_{m+1,k}^{r}}:=h_{m+1,k}^{r}:\Lambda_{m+1,k}^{r}\to% \Lambda_{m,k}^{r}\;$ and defined by setting ${\bf a}_{m+1}=0,\;{\bf a}_{(m+1)\mu}=0,\;\dots,{\bf a}_{(m+1)\mu_{1}\mu_{2}...% \mu_{k}}=0,\;\;\forall\;1\leq\mu_{i}\leq n,$ is called the $(m+1,k)$ horizontal projection or simply the h-projection when no confusion occurs; the restriction $h_{m+1,k}^{r}$ is called the $(m+1,k)$ horizontal projection of degree $r$. (ii) The graded ring homomorphism $\;v_{m,k+1}:\Lambda_{m,k+1}\to\Lambda_{m,k},\;$ such that $\;\forall r\in\mathbb{N},\;\;$ $\;v_{m,k+1}\mid_{\Lambda_{m,k+1}^{r}}:=v_{m,k+1}^{r}:\Lambda_{m,k+1}^{r}\to% \Lambda_{m,k}^{r}\;$ and defined by setting ${\bf a}_{1\mu_{1}\mu_{2}...\mu_{k+1}}=0,\;\;{\bf a}_{2\mu_{1}\mu_{2}...\mu_{k+% 1}}=0,\;\;{\bf a}_{m\mu_{1}\mu_{2}...\mu_{k+1}}=0,\;\;\forall\;1\leq\mu_{i}% \leq n,$ is called $(m,k+1)$ vertical projection or simply the v-projection when no confusion occurs; the restriction $v_{m,k+1}^{r}$ is called the $(m,k+1)$ vertical projection of degree $r$. (iii) The graded ring homomorphism $\;\pi_{m+1,k+1}:\Lambda_{m+1,k+1}\to\Lambda_{m,k},\;$ such that $\forall r\in\mathbb{N},\;\;$ $\pi_{m+1,k+1}\mid_{\Lambda_{m+1,k+1}^{r}}:=\pi_{m+1,k+1}^{r}:\Lambda_{m+1,k+1}% ^{r}\to\Lambda_{m,k}^{r}\;$ and defined by setting $\displaystyle{\bf a}_{m+1}=0,\;{\bf a}_{(m+1)\mu}=0,\;\dots,\,{\bf a}_{(m+1)% \mu_{1}\mu_{2}...\mu_{k}}=0,\;{\bf a}_{1\mu_{1}\mu_{2}...\mu_{k+1}}=0,$ $\displaystyle{\bf a}_{2\mu_{1}\mu_{2}...\mu_{k+1}}=0,\;{\bf a}_{m\mu_{1}\mu_{2% }...\mu_{k+1}}=0\;\;\mbox{and}$ $\displaystyle{\bf a}_{(m+1)\mu_{1}\mu_{2}\dots\mu_{k+1}}=0,\;\forall\;1\leq\mu% _{i}\leq n,$ is called the $(m+1,k+1)$ projection. The restriction $\pi_{m+1,k+1}^{r}$ is called the $(m+1,k+1)$ projection of degree $r$.
Definition 2.1. The tangent space to ${\mathcal{P}}_{{\overline{A}}}P$ at ${\tilde{\gamma}}$ is the linear space of all vector fields $t\mapsto{\tilde{v}}(t)\in T_{{\tilde{\gamma}}(t)}P$ along $\tilde{\gamma}$ for which $\frac{\partial{\overline{A}}({\tilde{v}}(t))}{\partial t}-F^{{\overline{A}}}% \left({\tilde{\gamma}}^{\prime}(t),{\tilde{v}}(t)\right)=0$ holds for all $t\in[0,1]$.
Definition 4.6 Let $R$ be a local ring with maximal ideal $\mathbf{m}$ such that $K-dim(R)=0$. We shall call it Artinian modulo the infinite radical in case $R/\bigcap_{n>0}\mathbf{m}^{n}$ is Artinian. Equivalently, if there is an integer $n>0$ such that $\mathbf{m}^{n}=\mathbf{m}^{n+1}$ and $R/\mathbf{m}^{n}$ is Artinian.
Definition 1. Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a triangulated category and $\begin{CD}X@>{x}>{}>Y@>{y}>{}>Z@>{z}>{}>W\end{CD}$ be three composable morphisms in $\mathcal{T}$. Consider the following triangle in $\mathcal{T}$: $\begin{CD}Z@>{}>{}>V@>{}>{}>Y[1]@>{y[1]}>{}>Z[1]\end{CD}$ Then the Toda bracket $\langle{z},{y},{x}\rangle$ is defined as the set of all morphisms $X[1]\to W$ which can be expressed as the composition of some $g:X[1]\to V$ and $f:V\to W$ making the following diagram commutative in $\mathcal{T}$: $\xymatrix{&&X[1]\ar[d]^{x[1]}\ar@{.>}[dl]_{g}\\ Z\ar[r]\ar[d]_{z}&V\ar[r]\ar@{.>}[dl]^{f}&Y[1]\ar[r]^{y[1]}&Z[1]\\ W}$
Definition 3.3. Let $\mathbb{T}$ be a geometric theory over a signature $\Sigma$ and $\phi(x_{1}^{A_{1}},\ldots,x_{n}^{A_{n}})$ a geometric formula over $\Sigma$. We say that a $\mathbb{T}$-model $M$ in Set is finitely presented by $\phi$ (or that $\phi$ presents $M$) if there exists a string of elements $\vec{\xi_{\phi}}:=(\xi_{1},\ldots,\xi_{n})\in MA_{1}\times\ldots MA_{n}$, called the generators of $M$, such that for any $\mathbb{T}$-model $N$ in Set and string of elements $(b_{1},\ldots,b_{n})\in MA_{1}\times\ldots MA_{n}$ such that $(b_{1},\ldots,b_{n})\in[[\phi]]_{N}$, there exists a unique arrow $f_{(b_{1},\ldots,b_{n})}:M\to N$ in ${\mathbb{T}}\textrm{-mod}({\bf Set})$ such that $f(\vec{\xi_{\phi}}):=(fA_{1}\times\ldots fA_{n})((\xi_{1},\ldots,\xi_{n}))=(b_% {1},\ldots,b_{n})$.
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathbb{T}$ be a geometric theory. A $\mathbb{T}$-model $U$ in a Grothendieck topos $\cal G$ is said to be a universal model of $\mathbb{T}$ if for any $\mathbb{T}$-model $M$ in a Grothendieck topos $\cal F$ there exists a unique (up to isomorphism) geometric morphism $f:{\cal F}\to{\cal G}$ such that $f^{\ast}(U)\cong M$.
Definition 12 For $(A,\delta,\epsilon)$ an observable structure in a $\dagger$-SMC ${\bf C}$ let $\Lambda:{\bf C}(I,A)\to{\bf C}(A,A)$ be defined by setting, for each point $\psi\in{\bf C}({\rm I},A)$, $\Lambda(\psi)=\delta^{\dagger}\circ(\psi\otimes\mathrm{1}_{A})\qquad\mbox{\rm i% .e.}\qquad\raisebox{-13.35pt}{\includegraphics[height=31.0pt]{images/lambda-% psi-defnbis}}\,,$ and we denote the range of $\Lambda$ by $\Lambda(A,A)$.
Definition 19 An observable structure $(A,\delta_{Z},\epsilon_{Z})$ with classical points ${\cal B}_{Z}$, and an observable structure $(A,\delta_{X},\epsilon_{X})$, satisfy comultiplicative commutation iff for all $z\in{\cal B}_{Z}$: $\delta_{Z}\circ\Lambda^{X}(z)=(\Lambda^{X}(z)\otimes\Lambda^{X}(z))\circ\delta% _{Z}\qquad\qquad\quad\mbox{\rm i.e.}\qquad\qquad\quad\raisebox{-14.35pt}{% \includegraphics[height=33.0pt]{images/mixcoloractionII}}\,.$
Definition 5 We call two mutually unbiased vector bases (= MUVBs), ${\cal V}=\{\left|v_{1}\right\rangle,\ldots,\left|v_{n}\right\rangle\}$ and ${\cal W}=\{\left|w_{1}\right\rangle,\ldots,\left|w_{n}\right\rangle\}$, coherent iff ${1\over\sqrt{n}}\sum_{i}v_{i}\in{\cal W}\qquad\text{and}\qquad{1\over\sqrt{n}}% \sum_{i}w_{i}\in{\cal V}\,.$ We call two mutually unbiased state bases (= MUSBs) coherent iff the deleting point of each is contained in the observable of the other.
Definition 15 Two observable structures $(A,\delta_{Z},\epsilon_{Z})$ and $(A,\delta_{X},\epsilon_{X})$ in a $\dagger$-SMC are called complementary if they obey the following rules: comp1 whenever $z:I\to A$ is classical for $(\delta_{Z},\epsilon_{Z})$ it is unbiased for $(\delta_{X},\epsilon_{X})$; comp2 whenever $x:I\to A$ is classical for $(\delta_{X},\epsilon_{X})$ it is unbiased for $(\delta_{Z},\epsilon_{Z})$;
Definition 9 An observable structure $(A,\delta,\epsilon)$ with classical points ${\cal B}$ is called a vector basis iff for all objects $B$ and all morphisms $f,g:A\to B$ we have $\big{[}\forall z\in{\cal B}:f\circ z=g\circ z\ \big{]}\Rightarrow\ f=g\,.$ It is called a state basis iff for all $B$ and all $f,g:A\to B$ we have $\big{[}\forall z\in{\cal B}\cup\{\epsilon^{\dagger}\}:f\circ z=g\circ z\ \big{% ]}\Rightarrow\ f=g\,.$
Definition 20 Observable structures $(A,\delta_{Z},\epsilon_{Z})$ and $(A,\delta_{X},\epsilon_{X})$ satisfy bialgebraic commutation iff: $D\cdot(\delta^{\dagger}_{X}\otimes\delta^{\dagger}_{X})\circ(1\otimes\sigma% \otimes 1)\circ(\delta_{Z}\otimes\delta_{Z})=\sqrt{D}\cdot\delta_{Z}\circ% \delta^{\dagger}_{X}\ \ \mbox{\rm i.e.}\ \ \raisebox{-20.35pt}{% \includegraphics[height=45.0pt]{images/bialgebralawbiscirc}}\!\!.$
Definition 4 We call a set of states of the form $\mbox{observable}\,\cup\{\mbox{unbiased state for that observable}\}$ a state basis. We call the unbiased state the deleting point.
