Definition 17 Two observable structures $(A,\delta_{Z},\epsilon_{Z})$ and $(A,\delta_{X},\epsilon_{X})$ in a $\dagger$-SMC are called coherent if they obey the following two rules: coher1 $\epsilon_{X}$ satisfies: $\sqrt{D}\cdot\delta_{Z}\circ\epsilon_{X}^{\dagger}=\epsilon_{X}^{\dagger}% \otimes\epsilon_{X}^{\dagger}\qquad\ \,\mbox{\rm i.e.}\qquad\,\raisebox{-11.85% pt}{\includegraphics[height=28.0pt]{images/Coherence1}}\ \quad$ coher2 $\epsilon_{Z}$ satisfies: $\sqrt{D}\cdot\delta_{X}\circ\epsilon_{Z}^{\dagger}=\epsilon_{Z}^{\dagger}% \otimes\epsilon_{Z}^{\dagger}\qquad\,\mbox{\rm i.e.}\qquad\,\raisebox{-11.85pt% }{\includegraphics[height=28.0pt]{images/Coherence2}}\ \quad$
Definition 22 The classical points ${\cal B}_{Z}$ of an observable structure $(A,\delta_{Z},\epsilon_{Z})$ are closed for another observable structure $(A,\delta_{X},\epsilon_{X})$ iff for all $z,z^{\prime}\in{\cal B}_{Z}$ we have $z\odot_{X}z^{\prime}\,\in\,{\cal B}_{Z}\,.$
Definition 10 We say that the monoidal tensor lifts vector bases iff for all vector bases $(A,\delta_{A},\epsilon_{A})$ with classical points ${\cal B}$ and $(B,\delta_{B},\epsilon_{B})$ with classical points ${\cal B}^{\prime}$, all objects $C$, and all morphisms $f,g:A\otimes B\to C$, we have that $\big{[}\forall(z,z^{\prime})\in{\cal B}\times{\cal B}^{\prime}:f\circ(z\otimes z% ^{\prime})=g\circ(z\otimes z^{\prime})\big{]}\ \Rightarrow\ f=g$ – hence it follows that the observable structure $(A\otimes B,\delta_{A\otimes B},\epsilon_{A\otimes B})$ is also vector basis. Similarly, the monoidal tensor lifts state bases iff $\big{[}\forall(z,z^{\prime})\in({\cal B}\times{\cal B}^{\prime})\cup\{(% \epsilon_{A}^{\dagger},\epsilon_{B}^{\dagger})\}:f\circ(z\otimes z^{\prime})=g% \circ(z\otimes z^{\prime})\ \big{]}\Rightarrow\ f=g\,.$ – hence it follows that $(A\otimes B,\delta_{A\otimes B},\epsilon_{A\otimes B})$ is also state basis.
Definition 1 The morphisms of type ${\rm I}\to{\rm I}$ in a monoidal category ${\bf C}$ are called scalars. For $c:{\rm I}\to{\rm I}$ a scalar we call the natural transformation $\left\{c\cdot 1_{A}:=\lambda^{-1}_{A}\circ(c\otimes 1_{A})\circ\lambda_{A}:A% \to A\bigm{|}A\in|{\bf C}|\right\}$ the scalar multiplication with scalar $c$. More explicitly, we can define $c\cdot f:=\lambda^{-1}_{B}\circ(c\otimes f)\circ\lambda_{A}=f\circ(c\cdot 1_{A% })=(c\cdot 1_{B})\circ f$ to be the scalar multiplication of morphism $f:A\to B$ with scalar $c$.
Definition 11 Let $(A,\delta,\epsilon)$ be an observable structure in a $\dagger$-SMC ${\bf C}$ and let ${\bf C}({\rm I},A)$ be the underlying set of points. We define a multiplication on points $-\odot-:{\bf C}({\rm I},A)\times{\bf C}({\rm I},A)\to{\bf C}({\rm I},A)$ by setting, for all points $\psi,\phi\in{\bf C}({\rm I},A)$, $\psi\odot\phi:=\delta^{\dagger}\circ(\psi\otimes\phi)\qquad\mbox{\rm i.e.}% \qquad\raisebox{-12.35pt}{\includegraphics[height=29.0pt]{images/odot-defn}}.$
Definition 23 A scaled bialgebra with dualisers is a pair of coherent observable structures which satisfy a modified form of bialgebraic commutation: $\raisebox{-32.15pt}{\includegraphics[height=68.6pt]{images/bialgebraALLBIS}}.$
Definition 14 The abelian group of endomorphisms of Theorem 5.2 is called the phase group, and its elements are called phase shifts.
Definition 2 A ${\dagger}$-symmetric monoidal category ($\dagger$-SMC) is a symmetric monoidal category equipped with an identity-on-objects contravariant endofunctor $(-)^{\dagger}:{\bf C}^{op}\to{\bf C}$ which coherently preserves the monoidal structure, that is, $(f\circ g)^{\dagger}=g^{\dagger}\circ f^{\dagger}\qquad 1_{A}^{\dagger}=1_{A}% \qquad f^{\dagger\dagger}=f\qquad(f\otimes g)^{\dagger}=f^{\dagger}\otimes g^{\dagger}$ together with the fact that the natural isomorphisms $\theta$ of the symmetric monoidal structure are all unitary, that is, $\theta^{-1}=\theta^{\dagger}$.
Definition 8 Given an observable structure $(A,\delta,\epsilon)$, a morphism $z:{\rm I}\to A$ is a classical point iff it is a self-conjugate comonoid homomorphism.
Definition 18 An observable structure $(A,\delta_{Z},\epsilon_{Z})$ with classical points ${\cal B}_{Z}$, and an observable structure $(A,\delta_{X},\epsilon_{X})$ with classical points ${\cal B}_{X}$, satisfy operator commutation iff for all $z\in{\cal B}_{Z}$ and all $x\in{\cal B}_{X}$: $\Lambda^{Z}(x)\circ\Lambda^{X}(z)=(x^{\dagger}\circ z)\cdot(\Lambda^{X}(z)% \circ\Lambda^{Z}(x))\qquad\ \ \ \mbox{\rm i.e.}\qquad\ \ \ \raisebox{-15.85pt}% {\includegraphics[height=36.0pt]{images/mixcoloractionIV}}\,.$
Definition 6 CPav An observable structure in a $\dagger$-SMC is an internal cocommutative comonoid $\left(\,A\ ,\ \delta:A\to A\otimes A\ ,\ \epsilon:A\to{\rm I}\,\right)$ for which $\delta$ is special and satisfies the Frobenius law, that is, respectively, $\delta^{\dagger}\circ\delta=1_{A}\qquad\mbox{\rm and}\qquad\delta\circ\delta^{% \dagger}=(\delta^{\dagger}\otimes 1_{A})\circ(1_{A}\otimes\delta).$
Definition 13 We call a point $\alpha:{\rm I}\to A$ unbiased relative to $(A,\delta,\epsilon)$ if there exists a scalar $s:{\rm I}\to{\rm I}$ such that: $s\cdot\alpha\odot\alpha_{*}=\epsilon^{\dagger}\quad\qquad\text{i.e.}\qquad% \quad\raisebox{-11.85pt}{\includegraphics[height=28.0pt]{images/Unbiassed_% newdef}}\,.$
Definition 21 A scaled bialgebra is a pair of coherent observable structures which satisfy bialgebraic commutation, that is, all together: $\raisebox{-32.15pt}{\includegraphics[height=68.6pt]{images/bialgebraALL}}.$
Definition 3 A vector $\left|\psi\right\rangle$ (or state $|\hskip-0.853583pt|\psi\rangle\hskip-1.707165pt\rangle$) is unbiased relative to vector basis $\left\{\left|v_{1}\right\rangle,\ldots,\left|v_{n}\right\rangle\right\}$ (or observable $\left\{|\hskip-0.853583pt|v_{1}\rangle\hskip-1.707165pt\rangle,\ldots,|\hskip-% 0.853583pt|v_{n}\rangle\hskip-1.707165pt\rangle\right\}$) if for all $i,j$ we have $\left|\langle v_{i}\mid\psi\rangle\right|=\left|\langle v_{j}\mid\psi\rangle% \right|\,,$ and two vector bases (or two observables) are mutually unbiased if each vector (or state) in one of these vector bases (or observables) is unbiased relative to the other vector basis (or observable).
Definition 16 The dualiser of two distinct observable structures $(A,\delta_{Z},\epsilon_{Z})$ and $(A,\delta_{X},\epsilon_{X})$ on the same object $A$ is $d_{ZX}=((\epsilon_{Z}^{\dagger}\circ\delta_{Z})\otimes 1_{A})\circ(1_{A}% \otimes(\epsilon_{X}\circ\delta_{X}^{\dagger}))\quad\mbox{\rm i.e.}\quad% \raisebox{-22.85pt}{\includegraphics[height=50.0pt]{images/dualiser}}\,.$
Definition 3.2. Given a reflexive globular set $G$, the type theory $\mathbb{T}[G]$ generated by $G$ (or $\mathbb{T}$ with $G$ adjoined) is obtained by augmenting $\mathbb{T}$ with the following additional symbols and rules: • A basic type $\;\vdash\;\ulcorner G\urcorner$; • Basic terms $\;\vdash\;\ulcorner g\urcorner:\ulcorner G\urcorner$, for each vertex $g\in G_{0}$; • Basic terms $\;\vdash\;\ulcorner f\urcorner:\ulcorner G\urcorner(\ulcorner g\urcorner,% \ulcorner h\urcorner)$, for each element $f\in G_{1}$ with $s(f)=g$ and $t(f)=h$; • Basic terms $\displaystyle\;\vdash\;\ulcorner\alpha\urcorner:\ulcorner G\urcorner^{\;n}% \bigl{(}\ulcorner\alpha^{0}_{0}\urcorner,\ulcorner\alpha^{0}_{1}\urcorner;\;% \ulcorner\alpha^{1}_{0}\urcorner,\ulcorner\alpha^{1}_{1}\urcorner;\;\cdots;\;% \ulcorner\alpha^{n-1}_{0}\urcorner,\ulcorner\alpha^{n-1}_{1}\urcorner\bigr{)}$ where $\alpha^{j}_{i}$ for $i=0,1$ and $0\leq j\leq n-1$ are as defined in Section 2.9, for each $\alpha\in G_{n}$; • New conversion rules: $\displaystyle\ulcorner i(\alpha)\urcorner\;=\;\mathtt{r}\bigl{(}\ulcorner% \alpha\urcorner\bigr{)}:\ulcorner G\urcorner^{n+1}\bigl{(}\ldots;\ulcorner% \alpha\urcorner,\ulcorner\alpha\urcorner\bigr{)}$ for every $\alpha\in G_{n}$.
Definition 3.9. Denote by $T_{\omega}$ the monad $\mathcal{T}(\mathbb{T}_{\omega})$. A reflexive globular set $G$ is a Martin-Löf complex (or ML-complex) if it is an algebra for $T_{\omega}$. We write MLCx for the Eilenberg-Moore category consisting of $T_{\omega}$-algebras and homomorphisms thereof. Similarly, we denote by $\textnormal{{MLCx}}_{n}$ the category of $T_{n}$-algebras for $n=0,1,2,\ldots$, where $T_{n}$ denotes the monad $\mathcal{T}(\mathbb{T}_{n})$.
Definition 4.2. (a) Let $\cal E$ be an elementary topos and $L$ be an intermediate logic presented by an axiom $\top\vdash_{\vec{x}}\top=\phi_{L}$ as above. The $L$-topology $j^{\cal E}_{L}$ on $\cal E$ is the smallest local operator $j$ on $\cal E$ such that the equalizer of $f_{L}$ and $g_{L}$ in $\cal E$ is $j$-dense; (b) Let $A$ be a locale and $L$ be an intermediate logic presented by an axiom $\top\vdash_{\vec{x}}\top=\phi_{L}$ as above. The $L$-sublocale of $A$ is the sublocale of $A$ corresponding to the subtopos ${\bf sh}_{j^{{\bf Sh}(A)}_{L}}({\bf Sh}(A))\hookrightarrow{\bf Sh}(A)$.
Definition 3.2. Let $\cal E$ be a topos and $j$ a local operator on $\cal E$, with associated sheaf functor $a_{j}:{\cal E}\to{\bf sh}_{j}({\cal E})$. (a) We say that $j$ (resp. the subtopos ${\bf sh}_{j}({\cal E})$) is weakly open if $a_{j}$ preserves the pseudocomplementation of subobjects; (b) We say that $j$ (resp. the subtopos ${\bf sh}_{j}({\cal E})$) is implicationally open if $a_{j}$ preserves the Heyting implication of subobjects.
Definition 3.8. (a) A morphism $f:L\to L^{\prime}$ of locales is said to be weakly open (resp. implicationally open) if the frame homomorphism $f:L^{\prime}\to L$ preserves the pseudocomplementation (resp. the Heyting implication) operation; (b) A sublocale of a locale $L$, with corresponding nucleus $j$ on $L$, is said to be weakly open (resp. implicationally open) if $j:L\to L_{j}$ preserves the pseudocomplementation (resp. the Heyting implication) operation.
Definition 2.1. Let $(\mathcal{C},\Sigma)$ be an $n$-angulated category, and $F(\mathcal{C})$ the free abelian group on the set of isomorphism classes $\langle A\rangle$ of objects $A$ in $\mathcal{C}$. Furthermore, let $R(\mathcal{C})$ be the subgroup of $F(\mathcal{C})$ generated by the following sets of elements $\begin{array}[]{rl}\{\chi(A_{\bullet})\mid A_{\bullet}\text{ $n$-angle in }% \mathcal{C}\}&\text{if $n$ is odd}\\ \{\langle 0\rangle\}\cup\{\chi(A_{\bullet})\mid A_{\bullet}\text{ $n$-angle in% }\mathcal{C}\}&\text{if $n$ is even}\end{array}$ in $\mathcal{C}$. The Grothendieck group $K_{0}(\mathcal{C})$ of $\mathcal{C}$ is the quotient group $F(\mathcal{C})/R(\mathcal{C})$. Given an object $A\in\mathcal{C}$, the residue class $\langle A\rangle+R(\mathcal{C})$ in $K_{0}(\mathcal{C})$ is denoted by $[A]$.
Definition 4.1. Let $(\mathcal{C},\Sigma)$ be an $n$-angulated category. (1) An $n$-angulated subcategory of $\mathcal{C}$ is a full subcategory $\mathcal{A}$ such that $(\mathcal{A},\Sigma)$ is $n$-angulated, closed under isomorphisms and the inclusion functor $\iota\colon\mathcal{A}\to\mathcal{C}$ is an $n$-angulated functor. (2) A subcategory $\mathcal{A}$ of $\mathcal{C}$ is dense in $\mathcal{C}$ if the following holds: every object in $\mathcal{C}$ is a direct summand of an object in $\mathcal{A}$. (3) A subcategory $\mathcal{A}$ of $\mathcal{C}$ is complete if the following holds: given an $n$-angle in $\mathcal{C}$ in which $n-1$ of the vertices are in $\mathcal{A}$, then the last vertex is an object in $\mathcal{A}$.
Definition 1. We say that a theory $T=(V,\sigma,\Xi)$ is prealgebraic if $\sigma$ is a balanced signature of type $(\Sigma_{\mathrm{f}},\Sigma_{\mathrm{r}},\mathrm{ar})$, where all relation symbols are binary and, for each $\varrho\in\Sigma_{\mathrm{r}}$, the axioms of $T$ include at least the axiom of reflexivity: $\forall x\in V:\varrho(x,x)$, and the axiom of transitivity: $\forall x,y,z\in V:(\varrho(x,y)\ \mathrm{AND}\ \varrho(y,z))\implies\varrho(x% ,z)$. In addition to this, $T$ will be called subalgebraic if it is prealgebraic and, for every $\varrho\in\Sigma_{\mathrm{r}}$, $\Xi$ contains also the axiom of antisymmetry: $\forall x,y\in V:(\varrho(x,y)\ \mathrm{AND}\ \varrho(y,x))\implies(x=y)$. Lastly, $T$ is called algebraic if $\Sigma_{\mathrm{r}}$ is empty (no relational symbols are permitted) and algebraic over $\mathbf{K}$ if, for each $\mathbf{K}$-model $\mathfrak{A}=(A,\sigma,\mathfrak{i})$ of $T$, there is one more $\mathbf{K}$-model $\mathfrak{A}_{\mathrm{a}}=(A,\sigma,\mathfrak{i}_{\mathrm{a}})$ of $T$ such that $\mathfrak{i}_{\mathrm{a}}(\varsigma)=\mathfrak{i}(\varsigma)$ for each $\varsigma\in\Sigma_{\mathrm{f}}$ and $\mathfrak{i}_{\mathrm{a}}(\varrho)$ is the equality relation on $A$ for all $\varrho\in\Sigma_{\mathrm{r}}$. Then, $\mathfrak{A}_{\mathrm{a}}$ is an algebraic $\mathbf{K}$-structure (see Remark 5), referred to as an algebraization of $\mathfrak{A}$, on the one hand, and an algebraic $\mathbf{K}$-model of $T$, on the other.
Definition 3. We say that $\mathfrak{A}_{1}$ is prehomomorphic [resp. subhomomorphic] to $\mathfrak{A}_{2}$ if there exist $\alpha\in\hom_{\mathbf{Sgn}_{1}}(\sigma_{1},\sigma_{2})$ and $\varphi\in\hom_{\mathbf{K}}(A_{1},A_{2})$ such that, for each $r\in R_{1}$, (i) $(\varphi\circ_{\mathbf{K}}\varsigma_{r,1},\varsigma_{\alpha(r),2}\circ_{% \mathbf{K}}\varphi^{n})\in\wp(A_{1}^{n},\mathcal{A}_{\alpha(r),2})$ (see Remark 4); (ii) $\varphi$ is a monotonic arrow $\mathcal{A}_{r,1}\to\mathcal{A}_{\alpha(r),2}$ in $\mathbf{Pre}(\mathbf{K})$ (see Example c.3 in Appendix A), where $n:=\mathrm{ar}_{1}(\varsigma_{r,1})$ (see Remark ). Then, we call $\Phi:=(\alpha,\varphi)$ a $\mathbf{K}$-prenorm [resp. $\mathbf{K}$-subnorm] or write that $\Phi:\mathfrak{A}_{1}\to\mathfrak{A}_{2}$ is a prenorm [resp. subnorm] of $\mathbf{K}$-models. In particular, a $\mathbf{K}$-prenorm $\mathfrak{A}_{1}\to\mathfrak{A}_{2}$ is said a $\mathbf{K}$-homomorphism if $\mathfrak{i}_{2}(\varrho_{\alpha(r),2})$ is the equality on $A_{2}$ for each $r\in R_{1}$.
Definition 5. Let $\{A_{i}\}_{i\in I}$ be an indexed family of $\mathrm{obj}(\mathbf{C})$ and suppose that the $A_{i}$’s have a product. A relation on $\{A_{i}\}_{i\in I}$ (in $\mathbf{C}$) is then any pair $(r,\Pi)$ for which $(r:R\to P)\in\bf C$ is a monomorphism [3, Section 1.7] and $(P,\Pi)\in\prod_{\mathbf{C}}\{A_{i}\}_{i\in I}$. This is called an $n$-ary relation if $I$ is finite and $n:=|I|$, and indeed an $n$-ary relation on $A$ if the $A_{i}$’s are all equal to one object $A$.
Definition 2. A $\mathbf{K}$-model $\mathfrak{A}=(A,\sigma,\mathfrak{i})$ of a theory $T=(V,\sigma,\Xi)$, with $\sigma=(\Sigma_{\mathrm{f}},\Sigma_{\mathrm{r}},\mathrm{ar})$, is said pivotal if the symbols of $\Sigma_{\mathrm{r}}$ have all the same ariety and either $\Sigma_{\mathrm{r}}=\emptyset$ or there exists $\varrho_{0}\in\Sigma_{\mathrm{r}}$ such that $\mathfrak{i}(\varrho)\subseteq\mathfrak{i}(\varrho_{0})$ for every $\varrho\in\Sigma_{\mathrm{r}}$. When this happens, $\mathfrak{i}(\varrho_{0})$ is called the pivot of $\mathfrak{A}$.
Definition 4. Assume that $\mathfrak{A}_{2}$ is pivotal and denote its pivot by $\leq$. Take $\varsigma_{2}$ to be a nullary function symbol in $\sigma_{2}$ (if any exists) and $\Phi=(\alpha,\varphi)$ a $\mathbf{K}$-prenorm $\mathfrak{A}_{1}\to\mathfrak{A}_{2}$. We say that $\Phi$ is (i) upward [resp. downward] semidefinite with respect to $\varsigma_{2}$ if $(\varsigma_{2}\circ_{\mathbf{K}}\varphi^{0})(a)\leq\varphi(a)$ [resp. $\mathcal{\varphi}(a)\leq(\varsigma_{2}\circ_{\mathbf{K}}\varphi^{0})(a)$] for every $a\in A_{1}$; (ii) upward [resp. downward] definite (with respect to $\varsigma_{2}$) if it is upward [resp. downward] semidefinite and $(\varsigma_{2}\circ_{\mathbf{K}}\varphi^{0})(a)\neq\varphi(a)$ for all $a\in A_{1}\setminus\bigcup_{\varsigma_{1}\in\alpha^{-1}(\varsigma_{2})}% \varsigma_{1}$, which is equivalently expressed by writing that $(\varsigma_{2}\circ_{\mathbf{K}}\varphi^{0})(a)\lneq\varphi(a)$ [resp. $\mathcal{\varphi}(a)\lneq(\varsigma_{2}\circ_{\mathbf{K}}\varphi^{0})(a)$] for every $a\in A_{1}\setminus\bigcup_{\varsigma_{1}\in\alpha^{-1}(\varsigma_{2})}% \varsigma_{1}$. (iii) indefinite (with respect to $\varsigma_{2}$) if it is neither upward nor downward semidefinite. On another hand, we say that $\Phi$ is trivial if $\varphi(a)=\varphi(b)$ for all parallel points $a,b\in A_{1}$.
Definition 6. Assume $\mathbf{C}$ is a category with binary products and a terminal object $\top$, and hence with all finite products [3, p. 40]. Pick $A\in\mathrm{obj}(\mathbf{C})$ and let $\varrho$ be a binary relation on $A$. We say that $\varrho$ is reflexive if $(a,a)\in\varrho$ for every $a\in A$; antisymmetric if, for all parallel $a,b\in A$, it holds that $(a,b),(b,a)\in\varrho$ only if $a=b$; transitive if, for all parallel $a,b,c\in A$, one has that $(a,c)\in\varrho$ whenever $(a,b),(b,c)\in\varrho$. Then, $\varrho$ is called a preorder (on the object $A$) if it is reflexive and transitive, and a partial order if it is an antisymmetric preorder: In the former case, we refer to $(A,\varrho)$ as a preordered object of $\mathbf{C}$; in the latter, as a partially ordered object, or pod.
Definition 3.2. Say that $d(F,G)\leq\varepsilon$ if $F$ and $G$ are $\varepsilon$-interleaved. Explicitly, $d(F,G)=\inf\{\varepsilon\geq 0\ |\ F\text{ and }G\text{ are }\varepsilon\text{% -interleaved}\},$ where we set $d(F,G)=\infty$ if $F$ and $G$ are not $\varepsilon$-interleaved for any $\varepsilon\geq 0$.
